THE GLORY OF THE GIGANTIC

There is drama, beauty and aesthetic appeal in the hard-to-come-by, very large, over-sized bottles of wine. Our friend, the late Gilbert Miller, always ordered his favorite wines and Champagnes in a larger size. Being curious, we asked him why.

Gilbert Miller responded that there were four reasons: 1. It was more impressive and festive. 2. Wines develop more slowly and live a longer life in the larger bottle. 3. There are fewer trips for the wine steward since he gets more glasses out of each bottle. 4. Theft is eliminated because one cannot easily hide a big bottle under his coat.

Impessed by Mr. Miller’s response, we decided to have the largest collection of big bottles in the country. We think w have succeeded. You will discover the magnums elsewhere in this brochure. On this page, we list only “Gods among wine’’—heroic bottles—bottles that will dazzle the recipient when given as a gift—and bottles that will add their own touch of lustre to your personal cellar.

Since these are hard to come by and are in short supply, we suggest that you order early.

BEERENAUSLESE AND TROCKENBEERENAUSLESE

THE MOST FABULOUS AND EXPENSIVE TABLE WINES OF THE WORLD

One glass of these wines represents a dramatic experience — rather like drinking and smelling a flower garden. The beeren means individual grapes are picked at the precise moment of ripeness. The trocken means ‘‘dry”’ or those wines that have almost turned into raisins. Even in Germany good examples of these command anywhere from $20.00 to $90.00 the bottle. The production of these wines is not a matter of profit but of pride because the proprietor can get much more money for the same acreage when making his usua! wines. These wines are made drop by drop. Here are wines to give as a Christ- mas present for a dramatic impact and to serve at the end of your holiday dinner instead
